Error Analysis: Index Out of Bounds / Undefined Access

Error Description:
This error means the code is trying to access a property (name, email) on a value that does not exist. In this case, users[i] becomes undefined, so reading user.name causes the crash.

Root Cause:
The loop is hardcoded to run 5 times (i < 5), but the API only returns 3 users. When i exceeds the array length, users[i] becomes undefined, causing the error when properties are accessed.

Solution:

function renderUserList(users) {
  const userListElement = document.getElementById('user-list');
  userListElement.innerHTML = '';

  for (let i = 0; i < users.length; i++) {
    const user = users[i];

    const userName = user.name;
    const userEmail = user.email;

    const userElement = document.createElement('div');
    userElement.innerHTML = `
      <div class="user-card">
        <h3>${userName}</h3>
        <p>${userEmail}</p>
      </div>
    `;

    userListElement.appendChild(userElement);
  }
}

Learning Points:

Never hardcode array limits
Always use array.length
Undefined array values cause runtime crashes
Always assume API data may be smaller than expected


Error Analysis: TypeError (map is not a function)

Error Description:
This error means .map() is being called on something that is not an array. The variable tasks has been overwritten and is no longer an array.

Root Cause:
Inside addTask, a new variable named tasks is declared, which shadows the global tasks array. This causes tasks to become an object instead of an array.

Solution:

let tasks = [];

function initApp() {
  tasks = [
    { id: 1, name: "Complete project proposal", completed: false },
    { id: 2, name: "Meeting with team", completed: true }
  ];
  displayTasks();
}

function addTask(taskName) {
  const newTask = {
    id: Date.now(),
    name: taskName,
    completed: false
  };

  tasks.push(newTask);
  displayTasks();
}

function displayTasks() {
  const taskListElement = document.getElementById('task-list');
  taskListElement.innerHTML = "";

  tasks.map(task => {
    const taskElement = document.createElement('div');
    taskElement.innerHTML = `
      <div class="task-item ${task.completed ? 'completed' : ''}">
        <span>${task.name}</span>
        <button onclick="toggleTaskStatus(${task.id})">Toggle</button>
        <button onclick="deleteTask(${task.id})">Delete</button>
      </div>
    `;
    taskListElement.appendChild(taskElement);
  });
}

Learning Points:

Variable shadowing breaks global state
Arrays must not be overwritten with objects
.map() only works on arrays
Always keep variable types consistent
Use clear naming to avoid collisions